-         HERCEGOVINA - CASES OF X., F.B., AND A.V.; 
-         THE PERSONNEL STRUCTURE AT OMARSKA CAMP 
 
IN WHAT POSITION, AND WHEN.) 
 
9. (U)  THE COMMANDER OF SECURITY AT OMARSKA 
(OBEZBJEDJENJA) WAS ZELJKO MEAKIC (29), AN INSPECTOR 
FIRST-CLASS IN THE BOSNIAN SERBIAN POLICE BEFORE THE 
WAR.  MEAKIC CAME FROM THE VILLAGE OF PETROV GAJ, 
NEAR PRIJEDOR.  BECAUSE.OF MEAKIC\'S POSITION AND THE 
AMOUNT OF TIME HE SPENT AT THE CAMP, MANY PRISONERS 
CONCLUDED, INCORRECTLY, THAT HE WAS THE OVERALL 
COMMANDER AT OMARSKA.  WHEN PRISONERS BEGAN ARRIVING 
AT OMARSKA IN LATE MAY, MEAKIC\'S DEPUTY WAS MIROSLAV 
KVOCKA (30), A SERB FROM THE NEARBY VILLAGE OF 
LAMOVITA.  KVOCKA HAD MUSLIM BROTHERS-IN-LAW WHOM HE 
                   LIMITED OFFICIAL USE 
 
 
                   LIMITED OFFICIAL USE 
 
PAGE 03        ZAGREB  02038  03 OF 09  161651Z 
TRIED TO HIDE IN HIS HOUSE.  WHEN THIS WAS FOUND OUT, 
HE WAS REPLACED AS MEAKIC\'S DEPUTY BY A MAN NICKNAMED 
BRK.  THIS CHANGE OF DEPUTIES OCCURRED IN LATE JUNE. 
 
------------------------ 
GUARD TEAM SHIFT LEADERS 
------------------------ 
 
10. (U)  OMARSKA CAMP HAD THREE REGULAR GUARD TEAMS. 
THE TEAMS WORKED TWELVE-HOUR SHIFTS, FROM SEVEN AM TO 
SEVEN PM.  THEY ROTATED CONSECUTIVELY, ONE AFTER THE 
OTHER.  THE THREE SHIFT LEADERS WERE: 
 
--  MLADO RADIC, NICKNAMED KRKAN 
--  MILOJICA KOS, NICKNAMED KRLE 
--  MOMCILO GRUBAN, NICKNAMED CKALJA 
 
11. (U)  RADIC IS A FORTY-YEAR-OLD ACTIVE POLICEMAN 
FROM LAMOVITA.  RADIC WAS IDENTIFIED AS THE MOST 
BRUTAL OF THE SHIFT LEADERS.  THE MOST HEINOUS 
TORTURES AND BEATINGS, AND THE LARGEST NUMBER OF 
DEATHS, TOOK PLACE DURING RADIC\'S SHIFTS.  KOS IS A 
MIDDLE-AGED WAITER WHO USED TO WORK AT THE HOTEL 
EUROPA IN OMARSKA BEFORE THE WAR.  KOS WAS IDENTIFIED 
AS A GENERALLY LESS BRUTAL SHIFT LEADER.  GRUBAN IS 
ABOUT THIRTY, FROM THE VILLAGE OF MARICKI.  HE IS IN 
           . 
THE POLICE RESERVE.  HE WORKED IN THE OMARSKA MINE 
BEFORE THE WAR.  GRUBAN WAS IDENTIFIED AS LESS BRUTAL 
THAN RADIC OR KOS.  EACH SHIFT TEAM COMPRISED FIFTEEN 
TO TWENTY GUARDS.       . 
