18.  (U) UPON DISEMBARKING, THE PRISONERS HAD TO RUN 
BETWEEN TWO ROWS OF \"CETNIKS\" WHO BEAT THEM WITH 
CLUBS AND RIFLES.  THERE WERE NO SHOOTING DEATHS AT 
THIS CAMP, BUT SOME DIED AS THE RESULT OF BEATINGS. 
THE WITNESS KNEW FOR CERTAIN OF TWO:  A JEWELER AND A 
                   LIMITED OFFICIAL USE 
 
 
                   LIMITED OFFICIAL USE 
 
PAGE 03        ZAGREB  00930  05 OF 05  071403Z 
BUTCHER FROM BIJELJINA.  THE PRISONERS WORKED EVERY 
DAY AND TRIED TO BE SELECTED TO WORK FOR LOCAL MEN, 
BECAUSE THEY FED THEM WELL.  MANY OF THE LOCAL PEOPLE 
WERE VERY SYMPATHETIC TO THE PRISONERS AND SAID THEY 
WERE UNHAPPY ABOUT WHAT ARKAN\'S AND CESA\'S SOLDIERS 
HAD DONE. 
 
19.  (U) THE WORST ABUSERS AT THE CAMP, BEGIC SAID, 
WERE A SERB NAMED GLIGOR AND TWO PRISONERS: FIKRET 
(AKA PIKLIC) AND \"SPAJZER\" (NFI) FROM ZENICA.  THE 
WITNESS WAS MORE AFRAID OF THE LATTER TWO THAN OF THE 
SERBS. 
 
20.  (U) WHEN THE ICRC CAME TO BATKOVIC, THE SERBS 
WOULD HIDE THE YOUNGEST AND OLDEST PRISONERS.  THEY 
WOULD ALSO HIDE A GROUP OF ABOUT EIGHT PRISONERS WHO 
WERE BEATEN EVERY DAY.  THIS GROUP INCLUDED A \"GREEN 
BERET\" FROM TUZLA, A MAN FROM BIJELJINA THEY ACCUSED 
OF BEING A SOLDIER, A BUTCHER FROM BIJELJINA, A CROAT 
NAMED ANDRIJA, AND A MAN WHO HAD ESCAPED AND 
 BEEN 
RECAPTURED.  DETAINEES HAD TO LIE TO THE ICRC ABOUT 
THEIR TREATMENT, BECAUSE SERB INFORMERS HAD 
INFILTRATED THE PRISON POPULATION. 
 
21.  (U) ON OCTOBER 13, 1992, THE WITNESS WAS 
RELEASED FROM BATKOVIC IN A REGULAR PRISONER 
EXCHANGE.  THE LARGEST NUMBER OF PRISONERS AT 
BATKOVIC DURING HIS TIME THERE WAS AROUND 1,600. 
THERE WERE STILL 500 TO 600 WHEN HE LEFT. 
 
