DARK.  THEN PRISONERS WERE CALLED OUT OF THE WAREHOUSE 
ONE BY ONE AND BEATEN.  THE WITNESS AND ANOTHER PRISONER 
NAMED ANDRIJA TUFEKCIC WERE THE MOST BADLY BEATEN, BUT 
THE WITNESS DID NOT KNOW WHY.  THEY WERE BEATEN WITH 
BOTTLES AND A FIRE HOSE NOZZLE.  SUCH BEATINGS CONTINUED 
FOR 10 DAYS.  THE WITNESS SHOWED SCARS ON HIS HEAD HE 
                   LIMITED OFFICIAL USE 
 
 
                   LIMITED OFFICIAL USE 
 
PAGE 03        ZAGREB  00945  02 OF 03  081147Z 
SAID WERE CAUSED BY THESE BEATINGS. 
 
6.  (U) THE WITNESS SPENT TWO MONTHS AT LUKA, WHERE 
BEATINGS WERE A DAILY OCCURRENCE.  HE SAID THAT IF A 
PRISONER HAD TO GO TO THE TOILET, HE WOULD ALWAYS RET 
URN 
BLOODY.  MONIKA, IN ONE CASE, POURED HYDROCHLORIC ACID ON 
ANDRIJA TUFEKCIC.  MONIKA, HE SAID, WAS ALSO KNOWN TO 
CASTRATE PRISONERS, SOMETIMES WITH BROKEN BOTTLES.  SOME 
PRISONERS WERE KILLED EVERY NIGHT, OFTEN BY SOLDIERS 
RETURNING FROM THE FRONT.  ON JULY 8 OR 9, ALL THOSE HELD 
PRISONER IN THE WITNESS\'S WAREHOUSE WERE TRANSFERRED ON 
10 BUSSES TO BATKOVIC PRISON CAMP. 
 
7.  (U) AT BATKOVIC, THE WITNESS SAID, GLIGOR (LNU) WAS 
ABSOLUTELY THE CRUELEST GUARD.  A FELLOW PRISONER CALLED 
SPAJZER ALSO ADMINISTERED SOME OF THE WORST BEATINGS. 
THE CAMP COMMANDER WAS NAMED VELJO. 
- 
8.  (U) WHEN THE WITNESS ARRIVED AT BATKOVIC THERE WERE 
ALREADY AT LEAST 600 PRISONERS THERE.  (NOTE:  THE 
WITNESS SAID THE HIGHEST NUMBER OF PRISONERS DURING HIS 
TIME AT BATKOVIC WAS ABOUT 1700.  END NOTE.)  UPON 
DISEMBARKING FROM THE BUSSES, THE PRISONERS HAD TO ENTER 
THE CAMP BETWEEN TWO ROWS OF \"CETNIKS\" WITH CLUBS, WHO 
BEAT THEM.  IN THE WAREHOUSE, THE EARLIER ARRIVALS WERE 
LYING FACE DOWN, THEIR HANDS BEHIND THEIR HEADS AND THEIR 
HEADS SHAVED.  ALL OF THEM WERE MEN EXCEPT FOR A WOMAN 
NAMED SENA FROM BRCKO, WHO HAD INSISTED ON ACCOMPANYING 
HER HUSBAND, A ONE-LEGGED MAN WHO HAD BEEN TORTURED. 
 
                   LIMITED OFFICIAL USE 
 
 
                   LIMITED OFFICIAL USE 
 
PAGE 04        ZAGREB  00945  02 OF 03  081147Z 
9.  (U) SOME PRISONERS DIED FROM THE DAILY BEATINGS IN 
THE CAMP.  OFTEN, SOLDIERS RETURNING FROM THE FRONT WOULD 
BE BROUGHT IN TO BEAT THE PRISONERS.  CERTAIN PEOPLE WERE 
SINGLED OUT FOR THE WORST BEATINGS, INCLUDING A SOLDIER 
NAMED NEDIM.  FOOD WAS VERY BAD, WITH ONLY ONE KILO OF 
BREAD FOR 15 PERSONS, AND A FEW SPOONSFUL OF THIN CABBAGE 
SOUP.  THERE WAS NO MEDICAL CARE, AND SOME OF THE OLD AND 
SICK DIED AS A RESULT.  THE OLDEST MAN THE WITNESS KNEW 
IN THE CAMP WAS BORN IN 1911.  ON THE HOTTEST DAYS, 
PRISONERS WERE LOCKED UP IN THE WAREHOUSES, WHERE THE 
HEAT WAS UNBEARABLE; TWO OR THREE PRISONERS WITH HEART 
PROBLEMS DIED AS A RESULT. 
 
10.  (U) EVERYTHING CHANGED WHEN ICRC FIRST VISITED THE 
CAMP IN AUGUST 1992.  WHEN THE FIRST VISIT WAS ANNOUNCED, 
100-150 PRISONERS WERE HIDDEN.  THESE INCLUDED THE 13 
MOST BADLY BEATEN AND THE VERY YOUNG AND VERY OLD.  THREE 
OF THE BADLY BEATEN MEN WERE ANDRIJA TUFEKCIC AND DVEVAD 
KAMBERI, BOTH FROM BRCKO; AND ELJUB SMAJIC FROM 
 
 
