THE DANE HAD BEEN CAPTURED BY THE SERBS AND THE HV HAD 
FOUND HIM WITH HIS HANDS TIED WITH WIRE.  TH 
E \"ARSK\" HAD 
USED HIM AS A HUMAN SHIELD DURING THE HV ATTACK ON THEM. 
SARINIC SAID THE DANE HAD DIED DURING THE RESCUE FLIGHT 
BACK TO THE MASH AT PLESO AIRPORT IN ZAGREB.  A POLISH 
UNMO (KOVALESKY - NFI) HAD DIED IN SERB-HELD TERRITORY, 
SARINIC SAID, BECAUSE THE SERBS HAD REFUSED TO ALLOW HIM 
ON A UN HELICOPTER TO PLESO THAT THE UN HAD ARRANGED AND 
CLEARED WITH THE CROATS. 
 
6.  AMBASSADOR GALBRAITH UNDERSCORED THAT THE SECURITY OF 
UN FORCES WAS OF UTMOST IMPORTANCE TO THE INTERNATIONAL 
COMMUNITY.  HV FORCES MUST GO AROUND UN OBSERVATION POSTS 
(UNOPS), HE SAID, NOT THROUGH THEM.  SARINIC RESPONDED 
THAT AKASHI AND JANVIER HAD ASKED THAT UN COMPOUNDS NOT BE 
                       CONFIDENTIAL 

 
 
 
 
 
                           CONFIDENTIAL 
 
PAGE 03        ZAGREB  02986  02 OF 05  052148Z 
VIOLATED.  THESE COMPOUNDS NOW HELD FOUR HUNDRED UN 
PERSONNEL AND THREE HUNDRED SERBS SEEKING REFUGE.  THESE 
SERBS WOULD BE FREE TO REMAIN IN CROATIA OR LEAVE FOR 
SERB-HELD B-H IF THEY SO WISHED.  THE CROATIAN AMNESTY LAW 
WOULD APPLY TO ALL WHO STAYED EXCEPT THOSE \"SPECIAL CASES\" 
GUILTY OF WAR CRIMES, HE ASSERTED.  THE UN WOULD BE 
ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ITS WORK IN KNIN, HE CONTINUED, AS 
SOON AS THE SECURITY RISK SITUATION ALLOWED THEM TO DO SO. 
KNIN WAS CURRENTLY UNDER A GENERAL AIR SIREN WARNING, HE 
SAID, BECAUSE SINCE 1430 LOCAL TIME, IT WAS BEING SHELLED 
FROM OBROVAC AND BENKOVAC. 
 
7.  SARINIC INSISTED THAT NOT A SINGLE HV SHELL HAD HIT 
THE KNIN UN COMPOUND.  IT WAS LOCATED OUT OF TOWN, AND THE 
HV FORCES HAD STRICT INSTRUCTIONS NOT TO TOUCH IT.  HE 
SAID ONE SHELL HAD FALLEN IN FRONT OF THE COMPOUND 
ENTRANCE.  CONFLICTING INFORMATION CONTINUED TO ARRIVE 
CONCERNING THE SITUATION INSIDE KNIN.  IN SARINIC\'S TALKS 
WITH THE UNPF LEADERS, GENERAL JANVIER HAD SAID THAT 
BODIES HAD LINED THE STREETS OF KNIN, YET AKASHI HAD 
CLAIMED THAT THERE WERE ONLY A FEW CASUALTIES. 
 
--------------------------- 
CONTINUED MILITARY ACTIVITY 
--------------------------- 
 
8.  THE SERBS CONTINUED TO MOUNT THE STRONGEST RESISTANCE 
IN SECTOR NORTH, HE SAID, BETWEEN GLINA AND PETRINJA.  HE 
EXPECTED OPERATIONS THERE TO CONTINUE ANOTHER 24-48 HOURS. 
ONE DOZEN TANKS STILL HELD OUT IN THE AREA.  THEY WERE 
UNABLE TO MOVE DUE TO MECHANICAL FAILURES, YET THEIR 
                       CONFIDENTIAL 

 
 
 
 
 
                           CONFIDENTIAL 
 
PAGE 04        ZAGREB  02986  02 OF 05  052148Z 
CANNONS STILL FUNCTIONED WELL.  TWO HV INFANTRY ATTACKS 
HAD BEEN UNSUCCESSFUL AT TAKING THEM OUT, SO THE ARMY HAD 
SURROUNDED THE TANKS AND WOULD NOT RISK FURTHER INFANTRY 
CASUALTIES. 
 
9.  AKASHI AND JANVIER HAD PROPOSED TO SARINIC A CESSATION 
OF HOSTILITIES AND WOULD PRESENT A PAPER TO SARINIC LATER 
THIS EVENING AT 1800.  SARINIC SAID THE GOC WOULD ONLY 
ACCEPT PROPOSALS THAT INCLUDED THE COMPLETE SURRENDER AND 
DISARMAMENT OF RSK FORCES IN BOTH THE SECTORS.  SARINIC 
WAS PREPARED TO STOP ALL MILITARY ACTIVITY TONIGHT IF THE 
SERBS WOULD AGREE TO THESE CONDITIONS. 
 
------------------------------------- 
BABIC AND POSSIBLE PEACE NEGOTIATIONS 
------------------------------------- 
 
10.  IN A TELEPHONE CONVERSATION EARLIER IN THE DAY, 
MINISTER OF DEFENSE SUSAK REQUESTED THAT THE AMBASSADOR 
PLAY A ROLE IN CEASEFIRE NEGOTIATIONS WITH THE SERBS. 
AMBASSADOR GALBRAITH THEN OUTLINED TO SARINIC HIS 
TELEPHONE CONVERSATION WITH MILAN BABIC THE DAY BEFORE. 
SARINIC SAID THAT BABIC COULD HAVE A USEFUL ROLE IN 
APPEALING TO ALL REMAINING RSK FORCES IN THE TWO SECTORS 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
                       CONFIDENTIAL 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
